root_causes: Special-code handling (97, 98, 99) is overridden by the final mapping to 2: the statement 'if not miss(S4) and HidS4DE_expected = $sysmis HidS4DE_expected = 2.' will set expected=2 for S4 values 97/98/99 because HidS4DE_expected was set to $sysmis earlier, so special codes are not preserved as system-missing as intended.

The script uses 'qTesting = 1' in the selection step instead of the expected isTest() check. If qTesting is not the survey's test-mode flag or has a different coding, the selection will not match the expected entry condition.
instructions:
Prevent the final mapping from overriding special codes. Either (preferred) add an explicit exclusion for special codes when assigning the '2' value, for example:
  if not miss(S4) and not any(S4,97,98,99) and miss(HidS4DE_expected) HidS4DE_expected = 2.
  This ensures S4 values 97/98/99 remain system-missing.

Or reorder statements so that the mapping to 2 occurs before setting special codes to $sysmis (i.e., set HidS4DE_expected = 2 for non-mapped values, then reset HidS4DE_expected = $sysmis for any(S4,97,98,99)).
Use miss(...) or miss(HidS4DE_expected) when testing for system-missing instead of directly comparing to $sysmis for clarity, e.g. 'and miss(HidS4DE_expected)'.

Ensure the test-mode condition matches the expected logic: either replace 'qTesting = 1' with the isTest() function (sel if (HidS4DE_mismatch = 1 and qCountry = 7 and isTest()).), or confirm/document that qTesting is the correct test-mode variable coded as 1 for test respondents. If qTesting is used, explicitly comment that it equals isTest() for maintainability.
